                    "author": {
                        "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=jorisvandenbossche",
                        "name": "jorisvandenbossche",
                        "key": "jorisvandenbossche",
                        "avatarUrls": {
                            "48x48": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452",
                            "24x24": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452",
                            "16x16": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452",
                            "32x32": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"
                        },
                        "displayName": "Joris Van den Bossche",
                        "active": true,
                        "timeZone": "Europe/Brussels"
                    },
                    "body": "There is actually already a \"sorting indices\" functionality available in Arrow, but it's not yet directly exposed in the Python library. With the recently added compute kernel registry, there is already some way to call this in python:\r\n\r\n{code}\r\nIn [1]: import pyarrow as pa                                                                                                                                                                                       \r\n\r\nIn [2]: arr = pa.array([1, 3, 0, 5, 3])                                                                                                                                                                            \r\n\r\nIn [3]: import pyarrow.compute as pc                                                                                                                                                                               \r\n\r\nIn [4]: pc.call_function(\"sort_indices\", [arr])                                                                                                                                                                    \r\nOut[4]: \r\n<pyarrow.lib.UInt64Array object at 0x7f0638532228>\r\n[\r\n  2,\r\n  0,\r\n  1,\r\n  4,\r\n  3\r\n]\r\n\r\nIn [5]: arr.take(pc.call_function(\"sort_indices\", [arr]))                                                                                                                                                          \r\nOut[5]: \r\n<pyarrow.lib.Int64Array object at 0x7f06385322e8>\r\n[\r\n  0,\r\n  1,\r\n  3,\r\n  3,\r\n  5\r\n]\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nbut the Python API can certainly be improved here.\r\n\r\nThe sort indices kernel currently only support the primitive numeric types + string/binary types, and not yet nested types.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=jorisvandenbossche",
                        "name": "jorisvandenbossche",
                        "key": "jorisvandenbossche",
